# Introduction to These Tutorials

Welcome to cpproad. This course assumes you're comfortable with Python and want to learn modern C++ (C++20 and later). C++ is fundamentally different from Python in ways that matter: it's compiled, statically typed, and gives you direct control over memory. These aren't obstacles—they're features that make C++ fast and powerful.

## What You'll Learn

These tutorials focus on practical, idiomatic modern C++. You'll skip outdated patterns (raw pointers, manual memory management in most cases) and learn the tools that make C++ safe and expressive. We emphasize the standard library, type safety, and writing code that's both efficient and clear.

## Key Differences from Python

**Static typing** means the compiler catches errors before runtime. You declare types explicitly, which feels verbose at first but becomes natural quickly.

**Compilation** happens once, before execution. Your program runs much faster than Python, but you'll see compiler errors that Python would defer until runtime.

**Memory management** is explicit in C++, but modern C++ (through smart pointers and RAII) automates most of it. You rarely need `new` or `delete` directly.

**Headers and linking** require more setup than Python imports, but the structure is learnable.

## How to Use This Course

Each lesson builds on previous ones. Code examples are real and runnable. When you see a concept that references an earlier lesson, that link will help you review.

Start with fundamentals: variables, types, and functions. Progress through standard library containers, memory management with smart pointers, and then more advanced topics. Practice writing code—reading alone isn't enough.

C++ has a learning curve, but it's rewarding. You'll write fast, safe code without sacrificing expressiveness.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <format>

int main() {
    auto name = "C++";
    auto year = 2024;
    std::cout << std::format("Welcome to {}! ({})\n", name, year);
    return 0;
}
```

The code above uses `std::format`, a modern C++20 feature for string formatting. It's safer and clearer than older approaches.

Ready to begin?

## Introduction to C/C++

C and C++ are compiled, statically typed languages that give you direct control over memory and machine resources — a sharp contrast to Python's managed runtime. Understanding their relationship helps frame everything else in this curriculum.

### C: the foundation

C was created in the early 1970s as a systems programming language. It is small by design: no classes, no templates, no standard containers beyond arrays. Its primary output is fast, portable machine code. The entire Unix operating system was rewritten in C, and it still underpins operating systems, embedded firmware, and performance-critical libraries today.

### C++: C with classes (and much more)

C++ began as an extension of C in 1983, originally called "C with Classes." The goal was to add object-oriented features without sacrificing C's performance. Over decades of standardization — C++11, C++14, C++17, C++20 — the language grew into something much richer: templates, the STL, lambdas, coroutines, modules, and ranges.

Modern C++20 code looks nothing like old C. For example, printing structured output with `std::format` (C++20) reads almost like Python's f-strings:

```cpp
#include <format>
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

int main() {
    std::string language = "C++";
    int year = 2020;
    std::cout << std::format("{} standard published in {}\n", language, year);
    return 0;
}
```

### Why learn C++ coming from Python?

Python is interpreted and garbage-collected. C++ is compiled directly to machine code and gives you manual memory control. This means:

- **Speed:** C++ programs routinely run 10–100x faster than equivalent Python for CPU-bound work.
- **Control:** You decide how memory is allocated and freed (and modern C++ gives you smart pointers so you rarely do it manually).
- **Portability at the metal:** C++ is the language of game engines, operating systems, compilers, and high-performance computing.

### C vs. C++: which will you write?

This curriculum focuses on C++. You will encounter C-style syntax occasionally — raw arrays, `printf`, pointer arithmetic — because C++ is a superset of most C. As covered in "Introduction to programs and programming languages," any text a compiler can process is valid input; C++ compilers accept nearly all valid C code. Prefer C++ idioms unless interoperating with a C library.

The standard used throughout is **C++20**. When a compiler flag like `-std=c++20` is required, it will be called out explicitly.

## Configuring Your Compiler: Build Configurations

Every C++ project typically needs at least two build configurations: **debug** and **release**. These are not language features — they are sets of compiler flags you (or your IDE) choose when invoking the compiler.

### Debug Configuration

A debug build prioritizes diagnosability over speed. Common flags (GCC/Clang) include `-g` to embed debugging symbols and `-O0` to disable optimization. With optimizations off, the generated code maps closely to your source, so debuggers like GDB can step through lines predictably. Debug builds also leave space for assertions and sanitizers (e.g., `-fsanitize=address`).

### Release Configuration

A release build optimizes for the end user. The debug symbols are stripped and optimization is raised, typically `-O2` or `-O3`. The resulting binary is faster and smaller but harder to debug because the compiler may reorder, inline, or eliminate code entirely.

### The `NDEBUG` Macro

The standard macro `NDEBUG` is automatically defined by many build systems when building in release mode. It disables `assert()` calls from `<cassert>`, so those checks carry zero runtime cost in production.

```cpp
#include <cassert>
#include <print>        // C++23; use std::cout if unavailable

int divide(int a, int b) {
    assert(b != 0);     // compiled out when NDEBUG is defined
    return a / b;
}

int main() {
    auto [x, y] = std::pair{10, 2};
    std::println("{}", divide(x, y));   // prints 5
}
```

### Warning Flags

Beyond optimization, treat warnings as a quality gate. `-Wall -Wextra -Wpedantic` surfaces a wide range of potential bugs. Adding `-Werror` promotes every warning to a hard error, forcing you to address them. This habit pays dividends long before you reach the chapters on undefined behavior.

### In Your IDE

Most IDEs (as covered in *Installing an Integrated Development Environment*) pre-create debug and release configurations. In Visual Studio the dropdown at the top reads **Debug** or **Release**. In CLion and VS Code with CMake, you set `CMAKE_BUILD_TYPE` to `Debug` or `Release`. Switching configurations recompiles the relevant translation units with the new flags — nothing about your source code changes.

Always develop and test in debug mode first; only profile and ship the release build.

