lessons.summary_md:
## `std::string_view` (Part 2)

`std::string_view` is a non-owning view over a character sequence. Part 1 introduced the basics; here the focus is on the sharp edges — ownership, lifetime, and modification restrictions.

### The Lifetime Trap

A `string_view` holds a pointer into memory it doesn't own. If the underlying string is destroyed, the view becomes a dangling reference — undefined behavior with no compiler warning.

```cpp
#include <string>
#include <string_view>
#include <print>

std::string_view dangling() {
    std::string local{"hello"};
    return local;           // local destroyed here; view points at freed memory
}

std::string_view safe_view(const std::string& s) {
    return s;               // caller owns s; fine as long as s outlives the view
}

int main() {
    std::string text{"world"};
    auto sv = safe_view(text);
    std::println("{}", sv); // ok
}
```

Never return a `string_view` built from a local `std::string`. The same applies to temporaries — `string_view sv = std::string{"temp"};` is immediately dangling.

### No Modification

`string_view` is read-only. There is no `operator[]` that lets you assign characters, and there is no `.append()`, `.replace()`, or similar mutating method. If you need to modify the content, copy it into a `std::string` first:

```cpp
std::string owned{sv};  // explicit copy
```

This deliberate limitation is what makes `string_view` cheap — it skips allocation entirely.

### Null Termination Is Not Guaranteed

`std::string` is always null-terminated; `string_view` is not. Passing `.data()` to a C-style function expecting a `\0`-terminated string is unsafe unless you can guarantee the view covers the whole string including its terminator.

### Useful Member Functions

- `.substr(pos, len)` — returns another `string_view`, no allocation
- `.remove_prefix(n)` / `.remove_suffix(n)` — trims the view in place
- `.find()`, `.starts_with()`, `.ends_with()` — same interface as `std::string`

### When to Use Each Type

- Accept read-only string parameters with `std::string_view` (replaces `const std::string&` and `const char*`).
- Store strings that must outlive their scope with `std::string`.
- Return strings from functions as `std::string`, never as `std::string_view` unless the caller's lifetime is clearly documented and controlled.

As covered in *Constant expressions* and *Constexpr variables*, `string_view` is also `constexpr`-friendly — a `constexpr string_view` can participate in compile-time evaluation where a `std::string` cannot.

