## Compound Statements (Blocks)

A **compound statement** (also called a **block**) is a sequence of zero or more statements enclosed in curly braces `{}`. The compiler treats the entire block as a single statement, which is why you can place a block anywhere a single statement is expected — inside an `if`, a `for`, a function body, or even freestanding in the middle of other code.

```cpp
#include <print>

int main()
{
    int x = 10;

    {
        int y = 20;           // y exists only inside this block
        x += y;               // x is still accessible here
        std::println("x inside block: {}", x);
    }
    // std::println("{}", y); // error: y is out of scope

    std::println("x outside block: {}", x);
}
```

### Why blocks matter for scope

Every name declared inside a block is **local to that block** — it comes into existence when control enters the block and ceases to exist when control leaves it. This is the foundation of **block scope**, which the rest of this chapter builds on.

When a name declared in an inner block matches a name in an outer block, the inner declaration **shadows** the outer one. The outer variable still exists; it is simply hidden. Shadowing is legal but usually a sign of confusing code, and many compilers will warn about it with `-Wshadow`.

### Blocks as a scoping tool

You can introduce a block anywhere to deliberately limit a variable's lifetime:

- Keeping a temporary resource (like a lock guard or a file handle) alive for only the few lines that need it.
- Reducing the visual noise of variables that are only relevant to one short calculation.
- Avoiding accidental reuse of a variable after its logical purpose is done.

This is not just a theoretical nicety — it directly enables RAII (Resource Acquisition Is Initialization), a pattern covered in later chapters, where object destructors run the moment the block ends.

### Nested blocks

Blocks can nest to arbitrary depth. Each level creates its own scope layer. Function bodies, `if`/`else` branches, loop bodies, and `switch` cases are all blocks, so scope nesting is happening constantly in everyday C++ code, even when you never write a freestanding `{}` pair.

