lessons.summary_md:
## Default Arguments

A **default argument** is a value supplied automatically when a caller omits that parameter. Declare defaults in the function declaration (usually in the header), not the definition.

```cpp
#include <print>

std::string formatScore(std::string name, int score, bool showRank = false, int rank = 0) {
    if (showRank)
        return std::format("{} — {} (rank {})", name, score, rank);
    return std::format("{} — {}", name, score);
}

int main() {
    std::println("{}", formatScore("Alice", 95));           // uses both defaults
    std::println("{}", formatScore("Bob", 88, true, 2));    // overrides both
}
```

### Rules and Restrictions

Default arguments must be **rightmost** — once you assign a default to a parameter, every parameter to its right must also have a default. You cannot leave a gap.

Defaults can only be specified **once** per declaration in a translation unit. If you forward-declare a function and define it separately, put the defaults on the declaration, not the definition.

Any expression that is evaluable at the call site is valid as a default: literals, `constexpr` variables, or even function calls — though mutable global state as a default is usually a maintenance hazard.

### Interaction with Overloading

Default arguments are *not* overloads; the compiler still sees a single function. This means they can create **ambiguous matches** with actual overloads. For example, if `formatScore(std::string, int)` is also defined as a separate overload, a two-argument call becomes ambiguous. Keep this in mind from the earlier lesson *Function overload resolution and ambiguous matches* — the resolution rules treat the defaulted version as one candidate, and a second overload as another.

Similarly, `= delete` (covered in *Deleting functions*) applies to entire overload sets. You cannot delete just the "version" of a function that uses its defaults; deleting the function removes all calls to it.

### When to Prefer Defaults vs. Overloads

- Use default arguments when the extra parameters are genuinely optional add-ons to the same behavior.
- Use overloads when the different parameter sets imply meaningfully different logic.

Mixing both strategies freely in the same overload set tends to produce hard-to-read resolution errors, so pick one approach per logical function and stay consistent.

