lessons.summary_md:
# Non-type Template Parameters

Template parameters don't have to be types. A **non-type template parameter** is a template parameter that holds a value rather than a type. You've seen type parameters written as `template <typename T>` — non-type parameters look like ordinary variable declarations inside the angle brackets instead.

```cpp
#include <array>
#include <format>
#include <print>

template <typename T, std::size_t N>
T sum(const std::array<T, N>& arr) {
    T result{};
    for (const auto& val : arr) result += val;
    return result;
}

int main() {
    std::array<int, 4> scores{10, 20, 30, 40};
    std::println("{}", sum(scores));  // prints 100
}
```

Here `N` is a non-type parameter of type `std::size_t`. The compiler deduces its value from the array passed in, so you don't write `sum<int, 4>(scores)` explicitly — template argument deduction (covered in *Function template instantiation*) handles it.

## What values are allowed

Non-type parameters must be **compile-time constant** values. Accepted categories in C++20 include:

- Integral types (`int`, `std::size_t`, `bool`, etc.)
- Floating-point types (`float`, `double`)
- Pointer and reference types
- Enumeration types
- Structural types (types whose members are all public and of the above kinds)

The most common are integral types, especially `std::size_t` for sizes and counts.

## Why use them

The key benefit is that the value becomes part of the type. `std::array<int, 4>` and `std::array<int, 5>` are distinct types — the compiler generates separate code for each, and bounds are known at compile time with zero runtime overhead. You can also use the parameter in `static_assert` or `if constexpr` to enforce or branch on constraints at compile time.

## Relationship to overloading

As discussed in *Function overload differentiation*, two function templates with different non-type arguments produce different instantiations, not overloads — but they behave similarly from the caller's perspective. A call like `sum(arr4)` and `sum(arr5)` dispatches to separate instantiated functions.

## Default values

Non-type parameters can have defaults just like type parameters:

```cpp
template <std::size_t N = 10>
void show_first(const auto& arr) { /* ... */ }
```

This mirrors how *Default arguments* work for ordinary functions, but applied at the template level.

