## Pass by const lvalue reference

In *Lvalue references* and *Pass by lvalue reference* you learned that a non-const lvalue reference lets a function modify the caller's object. Most of the time you do not want that — you want the function to read the argument without touching it. Adding `const` to a reference parameter gives you both goals at once: no copy *and* no accidental mutation.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

void print_info(const std::string& name, const int& count)
{
    // name and count are read-only here; modifying them is a compile error
    std::cout << name << " appears " << count << " time(s)\n";
}

int main()
{
    std::string word{"hello"};
    print_info(word, 3);        // lvalue — binds directly
    print_info("world", 1);    // rvalue — const ref extends lifetime
}
```

### Why not just copy?

For cheap types — `int`, `bool`, `char`, raw pointers — copying is fast and you should prefer pass by value. For types that own heap memory (`std::string`, `std::vector`, any large struct) a copy can allocate and copy every element, which is expensive. Pass by `const` reference avoids that allocation entirely.

### The rvalue bonus

As covered in *Lvalue references to const*, a `const T&` parameter can bind to both lvalues and rvalues (including temporaries and literals). A non-const reference cannot bind to rvalues, so `const T&` is strictly more flexible.

### Decision rule: when to use each form

- Pass by value when the type is small and trivially copyable (`int`, `double`, `bool`, pointers, iterators, `std::span`).
- Pass by `const T&` when the type is large or non-trivially copyable and the function only needs to read it.
- Pass by non-const `T&` only when the function must modify the caller's object (covered in *Pass by lvalue reference*).

A practical threshold: if `sizeof(T) > 2 * sizeof(void*)`, prefer `const T&`. For `std::string` and `std::vector` this is nearly always true.

### Common mistake: returning a const ref to a local

A `const T&` parameter is safe because it refers to something that outlives the function call. Never return a `const T&` that refers to a local variable — the local is destroyed when the function returns, leaving a dangling reference.

