lessons.summary_md:
## Pass by Address (Part 2)

This lesson extends what you learned in *Pass by address* and covers two practical patterns: using a pointer parameter as an optional argument, and deciding when to prefer pass by address over pass by reference.

### nullptr as a sentinel for optional arguments

Because a pointer can hold `nullptr`, you can use it to signal "no value provided". A reference cannot be null, so this pattern is exclusive to pointers.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

void greet(const std::string& name, const std::string* title = nullptr) {
    if (title)
        std::cout << *title << ' ';
    std::cout << name << '\n';
}

int main() {
    greet("Alice");            // prints: Alice
    std::string t{"Dr."};
    greet("Alice", &t);        // prints: Dr. Alice
}
```

Always check for `nullptr` before dereferencing. Dereferencing a null pointer is undefined behaviour, as covered in *Null pointers*.

### Pass by const address

Just as *Pass by const lvalue reference* prevents mutation of the referent, you can pass `const T*` to prevent the function from modifying the object being pointed to. The pointer itself is still passed by value, so reassigning it inside the function has no effect on the caller. If you also want to prevent the function from reseating the pointer, use `T* const`, but that is rarely needed.

Prefer `const T*` whenever the function only reads through the pointer.

### When to use pass by address vs. pass by reference

- **Prefer pass by reference** for mandatory arguments. References are never null, so callers cannot accidentally forget to provide a value. Code is cleaner and communicates intent.
- **Use pass by address** when `nullptr` is a meaningful input — i.e., the argument is genuinely optional or the absence of a value carries information.
- Never design an API that accepts a pointer but immediately dereferences it without a null check; if null is not allowed, accept a reference instead.
- `std::optional<T>` (C++17) is often a clearer alternative to nullable pointers for optional values, but pass-by-address remains idiomatic when you are handing off an address that already exists (e.g., an element inside a container).

### Key rules

- Check every pointer parameter for `nullptr` before use unless the contract explicitly forbids null.
- Use `const T*` when the function should not modify the pointed-to object.
- Default the pointer parameter to `nullptr` in the function signature to make the optional nature visible at the call site.

