# Introduction to Object-Oriented Programming

Object-oriented programming (OOP) organizes code around **objects** — bundles of data and the functions that operate on that data. Before classes, you wrote free functions that acted on variables passed in as arguments. OOP flips that relationship: the data and its behavior live together in one unit.

The three core ideas underpinning OOP are:

- **Encapsulation** — hiding internal state and exposing only what callers need
- **Inheritance** — building new types by extending existing ones
- **Polymorphism** — treating different types through a shared interface

This chapter focuses on **classes**, C++'s primary tool for defining your own types.

## Classes vs. Structs

A `class` groups member variables (data) with member functions (methods). In C++, `struct` and `class` are nearly identical — the only built-in difference is default access: `struct` members are `public` by default, `class` members are `private`. In practice, `struct` is conventionally used for simple data aggregates, and `class` for types with meaningful behavior and invariants.

## A Minimal Example

```cpp
#include <format>
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

class Book {
public:
    Book(std::string title, int pages)
        : title_{std::move(title)}, pages_{pages} {}

    std::string summary() const {
        return std::format("{} ({} pages)", title_, pages_);
    }

private:
    std::string title_;
    int pages_;
};

int main() {
    Book b{"Clean Code", 431};
    std::cout << b.summary() << '\n';
}
```

`Book` has two private member variables and one public method. The constructor uses a **member initializer list** (the `: title_{...}` syntax) to initialize members directly rather than assigning them in the body — prefer this style consistently.

## Why This Matters

Without OOP, related data drifts apart across your codebase. A `Book` might become three separate variables managed by scattered functions, with nothing preventing callers from putting the page count at -500. A class centralizes that data and enforces rules about it through `private` access.

The `const` qualifier on `summary()` is a promise: calling this method will not modify the object. Get into the habit of marking any method that only reads data as `const` — it communicates intent and enables the compiler to catch accidental mutations.

Upcoming lessons in this chapter will cover constructors in depth, access specifiers, and how to design a class interface that's hard to misuse.

