## Public and Private Members and Access Specifiers

Classes control which parts of their interface the outside world can touch. Every member — data or function — has an **access level** determined by an access specifier keyword placed above it in the class body.

The three specifiers are:

- `public` — accessible from anywhere the object is visible
- `private` — accessible only from within the class's own member functions
- `protected` — accessible from the class and its derived classes (covered when inheritance is introduced)

If you write a `class` without any specifier, members default to `private`. A `struct` defaults to `public` — the only real difference between `class` and `struct` in C++.

The core design principle here is **encapsulation**: hide internal state behind `private`, expose only a deliberate interface through `public`. This lets you change the implementation without breaking code that uses the class.

```cpp
#include <format>
#include <iostream>
#include <stdexcept>

class BankAccount {
public:
    explicit BankAccount(double initial) : m_balance{initial} {}

    void deposit(double amount) {
        if (amount <= 0) throw std::invalid_argument{"Amount must be positive"};
        m_balance += amount;
    }

    double balance() const { return m_balance; }

private:
    double m_balance{};
};

int main() {
    BankAccount account{100.0};
    account.deposit(42.5);
    std::cout << std::format("Balance: {:.2f}\n", account.balance());
    // account.m_balance = 9999;  // error: m_balance is private
}
```

The member `m_balance` (the `m_` prefix is a common convention for private data) is invisible to `main`. The only way to interact with it is through `deposit` and `balance`. This means the class can validate inputs, enforce invariants, or swap out its internal representation later without touching any calling code.

A few practical points:

- A single class body can have multiple `public:` and `private:` sections. Convention usually groups all public members first, then private.
- Member functions defined inside the class body (as in the example above) have full access to all private members regardless of which section they appear in.
- `const` member functions, covered in *Const class objects and const member functions*, interact with access control independently — `const` governs mutation, access specifiers govern visibility.

Prefer keeping data members `private` by default. Public data members are occasionally justified for simple aggregate types, but they surrender the ability to enforce invariants.

