## Introduction to the Copy Constructor

When you initialize an object from another object of the same type, C++ calls a special constructor called the **copy constructor**. Like the default constructor covered in *Default constructors and default arguments*, it is implicitly generated by the compiler if you don't write one — but understanding when it fires and how to write your own is essential once your classes manage resources.

### When the copy constructor is called

The copy constructor is invoked in three main situations:

- Direct copy-initialization: `Foo b = a;` or `Foo b(a);`
- Passing an object by value to a function
- Returning an object by value from a function (when copy elision doesn't apply)

### The implicit copy constructor

The compiler-generated copy constructor performs a **memberwise copy**: each data member of the source object is copied into the new object, in declaration order. For classes that only hold simple value types this is perfectly correct and requires no extra work from you.

### Writing your own copy constructor

The signature always takes a `const` reference to the same type. Without the reference, passing the argument would itself trigger a copy, causing infinite recursion.

```cpp
#include <format>
#include <string>
#include <iostream>

struct Point {
    double x{}, y{};

    Point(double x, double y) : x{x}, y{y} {}

    Point(const Point& src) : x{src.x}, y{src.y} {
        std::cout << std::format("Copy constructor: ({}, {})\n", x, y);
    }
};

int main() {
    Point a{3.0, 4.0};
    Point b{a};          // calls copy constructor
    Point c = b;         // also calls copy constructor
}
```

### Shallow vs. deep copy

The implicit copy constructor does a *shallow copy* — it copies the value of each member directly. For pointer members this means both objects point at the same underlying data, which is usually a bug. When your class owns a heap-allocated resource (a topic that connects to later chapters on dynamic memory), you must write a copy constructor that allocates a fresh copy of that resource — a *deep copy*.

### Relationship to const member access

Because the parameter is `const Point&`, only `const`-qualified member functions may be called on `src` inside the copy constructor body. This ties back to *Const class objects and const member functions* — the compiler enforces this automatically.

The copy constructor is the first piece of the **Rule of Three/Five**, which also involves the copy-assignment operator and destructor — all coming in later lessons.

