# Class Initialization and Copy Elision

## How Objects Are Initialized

When you initialize an object using a value of the same type, the compiler typically needs a **copy constructor** (covered in the previous lesson). But C++ has rules that allow—and sometimes require—the compiler to eliminate unnecessary copies entirely.

```cpp
#include <format>
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

struct Widget {
    std::string name;
    int value;

    Widget(std::string n, int v) : name{std::move(n)}, value{v} {
        std::cout << std::format("Constructed: {}\n", name);
    }
    Widget(const Widget& other) : name{other.name}, value{other.value} {
        std::cout << std::format("Copied: {}\n", name);
    }
};

Widget make() { return Widget{"Gadget", 42}; }

int main() {
    Widget w = make();  // "Constructed: Gadget" — copy elided
}
```

Running this prints only the constructor message, never the copy constructor. The copy is eliminated, not just skipped silently—the object is constructed directly in its final location.

## Named Return Value Optimization (NRVO) and Mandatory Elision

There are two distinct situations:

- **Mandatory copy elision (C++17+):** When you initialize an object directly from a temporary (a *prvalue*), the copy is *guaranteed* to be elided. The temporary is never materialized as a separate object at all.
- **NRVO:** When a function returns a named local variable of the return type, the compiler is *permitted* (but not required) to construct it directly in the caller's storage, skipping the copy.

## Initialization Forms

Several initialization syntaxes may invoke copy construction, but copy elision often removes the actual copy:

- `Widget w = make();` — direct-initialization from a prvalue; copy elided (mandatory since C++17)
- `Widget w = other;` — copy-initialization from an lvalue; copy constructor *is* called
- `Widget w{other};` — direct-list-initialization; copy constructor called
- `return localWidget;` — NRVO candidate; copy may be elided

## Why This Matters

Because copy elision can eliminate calls to the copy constructor, you should not write logic with observable side effects inside the copy constructor and depend on it running a specific number of times. The *as-if* rule does not apply here—the standard explicitly permits (or mandates) elision even when the copy constructor has side effects.

This interacts with the *Constructor member initializer lists* and *Temporary class objects* lessons: temporaries created during construction are themselves subject to these same elision rules.

