## Converting Constructors and the `explicit` Keyword

A **converting constructor** is any constructor that can be called with a single argument (or that has all parameters after the first defaulted). The compiler uses these constructors to perform **implicit conversions** — silently turning one type into another when the context demands it.

```cpp
#include <print>

struct Temperature {
    explicit Temperature(double celsius) : m_celsius{celsius} {}
    double m_celsius;
};

void print_temp(Temperature t) {
    std::print("Temp: {}°C\n", t.m_celsius);
}

int main() {
    print_temp(Temperature{98.6}); // OK: direct initialization
    // print_temp(98.6);           // Error: implicit conversion blocked
}
```

Without `explicit`, calling `print_temp(98.6)` would silently construct a `Temperature` from a bare `double`. That looks harmless here, but in real code implicit conversions routinely cause bugs that are hard to spot — especially when multiple converting constructors exist and the compiler picks one you didn't intend.

### When implicit conversion fires

The compiler attempts an implicit conversion in three main situations:

- **Copy initialization** — `Temperature t = 98.6;`
- **Passing an argument** — `print_temp(98.6);`
- **Returning a value** — `return 98.6;` from a function returning `Temperature`

Marking a constructor `explicit` disables all three. Direct initialization (`Temperature t{98.6}`) and explicit casts (`static_cast<Temperature>(98.6)`) still work fine.

### The rule of thumb

Mark single-argument constructors `explicit` by default. Only omit it when implicit conversion is genuinely meaningful and unsurprising — `std::string` accepting a `const char*` is the classic example where the conversion is so natural that forcing `explicit` would just be noise.

Multi-parameter constructors can't be called with a single argument, so they aren't converting constructors — but if default arguments reduce the effective call to one argument (covered in **Default constructors and default arguments**), the same logic applies and `explicit` is still worth considering.

### Interaction with copy constructors

As seen in **Introduction to the copy constructor**, the copy constructor is also a single-argument constructor. You can mark it `explicit` too, though this is rare. Doing so prevents copy initialization (`Temperature t = other_temp;`) while still allowing direct initialization (`Temperature t{other_temp};`).

Keeping `explicit` as your default habit catches an entire class of silent type-mismatch bugs before they compile.

