}

lessons.summary_md:
## Static Member Variables

A **static member variable** belongs to the class itself, not to any individual instance. Every object of the class shares the exact same variable. This is distinct from regular member variables, which each instance owns a separate copy of.

### Declaration and definition

Declare a static member inside the class body with the `static` keyword. Historically, non-const static members required a separate out-of-class definition to allocate storage:

```cpp
// Widget.h
class Widget {
public:
    static int s_count;       // declaration only
    Widget() { ++s_count; }
    ~Widget() { --s_count; }
};

// Widget.cpp
int Widget::s_count = 0;      // definition + initializer
```

Since C++17 you can skip the separate definition by adding `inline`:

```cpp
class Widget {
public:
    inline static int s_count = 0;  // definition inside class — C++17
    Widget() { ++s_count; }
    ~Widget() { --s_count; }
};
```

Prefer `inline static` for new code — it eliminates the matching `.cpp` definition and the ODR pitfalls that come with it. (The `inline` keyword here means "exactly one definition is allowed across all translation units", not anything about inlining calls.)

### constexpr static

For compile-time constants, use `constexpr static`. No `inline` is needed because `constexpr` implies `inline` for static members:

```cpp
class MathConstants {
public:
    static constexpr double pi = 3.14159265358979;
};
```

Access via `MathConstants::pi` anywhere without creating an object.

### Access

Static members exist even when no objects exist. Access them through the class name (preferred) or through any instance:

- `Widget::s_count` — preferred, makes the shared nature obvious
- `w.s_count` — works but misleads the reader into thinking it belongs to `w`

### When to use

- Tracking how many instances exist (instance counters)
- Storing class-wide configuration or caches that all instances read
- Compile-time constants associated with a type (prefer `constexpr static`)

Avoid using static members as global variable replacements — they carry the same lifetime and initialization-order risks. Covered in "The hidden `this` pointer": static members have no implicit `this` parameter, so static *member functions* (covered next lesson) cannot access non-static members.

