std::vector<int> reverseVector(std::vector<int> src) {
    std::vector<int> result;
    result.reserve(src.size());
    while (!src.empty()) {
        result.push_back(src.back());
        src.pop_back();
    }
    return result;
}

int main() {
    int n;
    std::cin >> n;

    std::vector<int> data;
    data.reserve(n);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        int x;
        std::cin >> x;
        data.push_back(x);
    }

    std::vector<int> rev = reverseVector(data);

    for (int i = 0; i < static_cast<int>(rev.size()); ++i) {
        if (i > 0) std::cout << ' ';
        std::cout << rev[i];
    }
    std::cout << '\n';
    return 0;
}

lessons.summary_md:
## Introduction to Smart Pointers and Move Semantics

Raw pointers in C++ require manual `new`/`delete` pairing. Miss a `delete` and you leak memory; delete twice and you get undefined behavior. Smart pointers eliminate both problems by tying object lifetime to a wrapping object whose destructor handles cleanup automatically — a direct application of RAII (Resource Acquisition Is Initialization).

The standard library provides three smart pointer types in `<memory>`:

- `std::unique_ptr<T>` — sole ownership; one pointer owns the object at a time
- `std::shared_ptr<T>` — shared ownership; a reference count tracks how many pointers co-own the object
- `std::weak_ptr<T>` — non-owning observer of a `shared_ptr`; breaks reference cycles

**Move semantics** are what make `unique_ptr` work. A `unique_ptr` cannot be *copied* — that would create two owners — but it can be *moved*, transferring ownership to a new pointer and leaving the source empty. The compiler represents this through *rvalue references* (`T&&`), and `std::move` explicitly casts a named variable to an rvalue so the move constructor or move assignment operator is selected.

```cpp
#include <memory>
#include <print>

struct Widget {
    int id;
    ~Widget() { std::println("Widget {} destroyed", id); }
};

int main() {
    auto a = std::make_unique<Widget>(42);  // a owns the Widget
    auto b = std::move(a);                 // ownership transferred to b
    // a is now nullptr; b holds the Widget
    std::println("b owns Widget {}", b->id);
}   // Widget 42 destroyed here — automatically
```

`std::make_unique` is preferred over `new` because it's exception-safe and keeps allocation and ownership together in one expression.

A few practical rules:

- Default to `unique_ptr`; reach for `shared_ptr` only when multiple owners genuinely make sense.
- Prefer passing raw pointers or references into functions that don't affect ownership — the caller retains the smart pointer.
- `std::move` doesn't move anything by itself; it just enables the compiler to call the move overload. The actual transfer happens inside the move constructor.

Later lessons in this chapter cover move constructors and move assignment in detail, and the reference-counting mechanics behind `shared_ptr`. For now, the core mental model is: smart pointers own memory, move semantics transfer ownership, and destructors clean up.

